## Math

### Typst math

Use TeX math. Pandoc will convert to typst math.

````{.markdown filename="equations.qmd" .code-overflow-wrap}
The mean on-time rate, $\bar{x}$, summarises performance across all routes.

$$
\bar{x} = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i
$$ {#eq-mean}

````

![Inline and display math rendered in Typst](images/typst-math-equations.png){#fig-typst-math-equations .border fig-alt="A PDF showing an inline mean symbol in a sentence and a numbered display equation for the sample mean."}

### Alt text

````{.markdown filename="equations.qmd" .code-overflow-wrap}
$$
\bar{x} = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i
$$ {#eq-mean alt="Sample mean: sum of all values divided by the number of observations"}

````

![Display equation with alt text](images/typst-math-equations-alt.png){#fig-typst-math-equations-alt .border fig-alt="A PDF showing a numbered display equation for the sample mean."}

### Theorems

````{.markdown filename="theorem.qmd" .code-overflow-wrap}
::: {#thm-chebyshev}
## Chebyshev's Inequality

For a random variable $X$ with mean $\mu$ and variance $\sigma^2$, for any $k > 0$:

$$P(|X - \mu| \geq k\sigma) \leq \frac{1}{k^2}$$
:::

::: proof
Apply Markov's inequality to the non-negative random variable $(X - \mu)^2$.
:::

````

Control the appearance with `theorem-appearance`:

```{.yaml filename="_quarto-fancy.yml"}
format:
  typst:
    theorem-appearance: fancy
```

The default is `simple`

::: {#fig-typst-math-theorem}
::: {layout-ncol=2}
![`simple`](images/typst-math-theorem.png){#fig-typst-math-theorem-simple .border fig-alt="A theorem in simple LaTeX style with bold title and italic body text."}

![`fancy`](images/typst-math-theorem-fancy.png){#fig-typst-math-theorem-fancy .border fig-alt="A theorem in a rounded box with an orange header."}

![`clouds`](images/typst-math-theorem-clouds.png){#fig-typst-math-theorem-clouds .border fig-alt="A theorem with a soft pink background and rounded corners."}

![`rainbow`](images/typst-math-theorem-rainbow.png){#fig-typst-math-theorem-rainbow .border fig-alt="A theorem with a red left border and red title."}
